My great grandfather & great grandmother remained in Fleetwood the rest of their long lives and became devout Quakers. I have very fond memories of them both. None of this would have been possible without Fleetwood Freeport and I’ll be forever indebted to Dishy Rishi. What a guy.

My Nan used to work in Lofthouse’s making Fisherman’s Friends lozenges as young adult, and during the Second World War made bolts for aircraft at Vickers in Blackpool, where she met my Grandfather (who whisked her off to ‘the land of milk and honey’ (Newton le Willows!))

I like Fleetwood a lot, my maternal grandmother’s family are from there. My Great Grandfather fought in the First World War on HMS Reliant and went on to be a butcher in the town and live on Broadway https://t.co/h1BctCr8ao

Fleetwood, now known as ‘the London of the North’ thanks to its Freeport (opened in 1997 when Dishy Rishi was 17 (and on the back benches, obvs)) has never looked back. Beeching fully reversed. What a twerp. https://t.co/NemesZBjmd
